@fortelabs Knowledge work involves many questions of utility: Is it useful? Does it work?

They’re mostly personal and subjective, so they’re easier to answer. 

And a second brain can certainly help.

@fortelabs But knowledge work also involves questions of veracity: Is it true?

Those are harder. They’re objective and require outside testimony (often before you know you need it). 

For that, you really need something more like a collective brain.

@vgr I feel like people tend to work on what they think they’re good at (which might be another way of saying the same thing).

The more accurate they are on that assessment, the more successful they become.

For most, perceived competence is far more of a motivation than money.

@renai_zen @fortelabs The internet is a collective brain. But it's broken.

Information is manipulated by people (media, academia, &amp; government) who obscure truth to further their own agendas and filtered by gatekeepers who are driven by advertisers and algorithms, not truth.

We need better tools.

